"14","J","Ayyappan, N; Stephen, A; Muthusankar, G; Jeyakumar, S; Presena, J",NA,NA,NA,"Ayyappan, N.; Stephen, A.; Muthusankar, G.; Jeyakumar, S.; Presena, J.",NA,NA,"Spatio-temporal changes in fringe mangrove extent in Pondicherry, India after two phenomenal perturbations: tsunami and cyclone Thane","TROPICAL ECOLOGY",NA,NA,"English","Article",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Avicennia; disturbance; dynamics; monodominance; recovery; tree density; vegetation cover","RHIZOPHORA-APICULATA; AVICENNIA-MARINA; NICOBAR ISLANDS; SOUTHEAST COAST; FORESTS; IMPACT; ECOSYSTEMS; GROWTH; ESTABLISHMENT; REGENERATION","Growing pressures on mangroves throughout the world, highlight the need for studies of vegetation across spatio-temporal scales even in relict patches for ecosystem conservation. Mangroves experience human pressure due to coastal development and are also subjected to environmental stress such as cyclones, tsunami, floods, and sea-level rise, often taking decades to recover from these stresses. We estimated changes in mangrove vegetation in the Ariankuppam estuary on the southeastern coast of peninsular India after two phenomenal perturbations, the 2004 tsunami and 2011 cyclone Thane. We compared land cover maps of mangroves from 2005, 2010, and 2011 with 2004 mangrove vegetation maps to detect change in areal extent of mangrove zones. We inventoried all stems >= 10 cm gbh in 34 quadrats (5 m x 5 m) prior to the 2011 cyclone, immediately following the cyclone, and eighteen months later to document damages and recovery. The site harbours 2988 trees ha(-1) for stems >= 10 cm gbh. We found four distinct mangrove zones in 2005 (15.54 ha), and five distinct mangrove zones in 2010 (41.73 ha) and 2011 (40.65 ha). The tsunami and subsequent activities such as dragging the boats swept ashore and dredging resulted in 48 % loss of mangroves. The increase in mangrove area observed during 2010 and 2011 was due to the recovery potential of Avicennia and restoration programs. Cyclonic impact and recovery status inventories revealed that among the different zones, the monodominant Avicennia zone experienced severe damage and the mixed Avicennia zone showed slow recovery. The full impacts on the ecosystem from extreme stochastic events; however, can only be determined with long-term monitoring.","[Ayyappan, N.; Stephen, A.; Jeyakumar, S.] French Inst Pondicherry, Dept Ecol, Pondicherry 605001, India; [Muthusankar, G.] French Inst Pondicherry, Geomat & Appl Informat Lab, Pondicherry 605001, India; [Jeyakumar, S.] VHNSN Coll, Dept Bot, Virudunagar 626001, India; [Presena, J.] Indira Gandhi Coll, Dept Biol Sci, Pondicherry 605009, India; [Stephen, A.] REM Vivekananda Coll, Dept Plant Biol & Plant Biotechnol, Chennai 600004, Tamil Nadu, India","Ayyappan, N (corresponding author), French Inst Pondicherry, Dept Ecol, Pondicherry 605001, India.","ayyappan.n@ifpindia.org","Gowrappan, Muthusankar/AAE-6959-2020; Narayanan, Ayyappan/AAS-7101-2021","Gowrappan, Muthusankar/0000-0001-9552-7259; S, JEYAKUMAR/0000-0001-8031-7419",NA,NA,NA,43,2,2,1,32,"SCIENTIFIC PUBLISHERS","JODHPUR","5A, NEW PALI RD, JODHPUR, RAJASTHAN 342 001, INDIA","0564-3295","2661-8982",NA,"TROP ECOL","Trop. Ecol.","MAY",2016,"57","2",NA,NA,NA,NA,"361","368",NA,NA,NA,NA,8,"Ecology","Environmental Sciences & Ecology","DD8XR","WOS:000370210700021",NA,NA,NA,NA,"2021-09-23",NA
"15","J","Badejo, O; Skaldina, O; Gilev, A; Sorvari, J",NA,NA,NA,"Badejo, Oluwatobi; Skaldina, Oksana; Gilev, Aleksei; Sorvari, Jouni",NA,NA,"Benefits of insect colours: a review from social insect studies","OECOLOGIA",NA,NA,"English","Review",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Aposematism; Camouflage; Colouration; Thermal melanism; Hymenoptera","THERMAL MELANISM; HYMENOPTERA-FORMICIDAE; ECOSYSTEM SERVICES; VESPULA-VULGARIS; BATESIAN MIMICRY; CUTICULAR COLOR; IMMUNE FUNCTION; MOLECULAR-BASIS; WASPS; ANTS","Insect colours assist in body protection, signalling, and physiological adaptations. Colours also convey multiple channels of information. These channels are valuable for species identification, distinguishing individual quality, and revealing ecological or evolutionary aspects of animals' life. During recent years, the emerging interest in colour research has been raised in social hymenopterans such as ants, wasps, and bees. These insects provide important ecosystem services and many of those are model research organisms. Here we review benefits that various colour types give to social insects, summarize practical applications, and highlight further directions. Ants might use colours principally for camouflage, however the evolutionary function of colour in ants needs more attention; in case of melanin colouration there is evidence for its interrelation with thermoregulation and pathogen resistance. Colours in wasps and bees have confirmed linkages to thermoregulation, which is increasingly important in face of global climate change. Besides wasps use colours for various types of signalling. Colour variations of well chemically defended social insects are the mimetic model for unprotected organisms. Despite recent progress in molecular identification of species, colour variations are still widely in use for species identification. Therefore, further studies on variability is encouraged. Being closely interconnected with physiological and biochemical processes, insect colouration is a great source for finding new ecological indicators and biomarkers. Due to novel digital imaging techniques, software, and artificial intelligence there are emerging possibilities for new advances in this topic. Further colour research in social insects should consider specific features of sociality.","[Badejo, Oluwatobi; Skaldina, Oksana; Sorvari, Jouni] Univ Eastern Finland, Dept Environm & Biol Sci, Yliopistonranta 1,POB 1627, Kuopio 70211, Finland; [Gilev, Aleksei] Russian Acad Sci, Inst Plant & Anim Ecol IPAE, Ural Ctr, 8 Marta St,202, Ekaterinburg 620144, Russia; [Gilev, Aleksei] Ural Fed Univ, Russian Acad Sci, Inst Plant & Anim Ecol, Ural Branch, Mira St 19, Ekaterinburg 620002, Russia; [Sorvari, Jouni] Univ Turku, Dept Biol, Turku 20014, Finland","Skaldina, O (corresponding author), Univ Eastern Finland, Dept Environm & Biol Sci, Yliopistonranta 1,POB 1627, Kuopio 70211, Finland.","oluwatobi.badejo@uef.fi; oksana.skaldina@uef.fi; gilev123@yandex.ru; jouni.sorvari@utu.fi","Gilev, Alexey/ABF-8742-2020","Gilev, Alexey/0000-0002-0404-6343; Badejo, Oluwatobi/0000-0001-9928-9059; Skaldina, Oksana/0000-0001-8674-7110","University of Eastern Finland (UEF) including Kuopio University Hospital","Open access funding provided by University of Eastern Finland (UEF) including Kuopio University Hospital.",NA,150,3,3,9,28,"SPRINGER","NEW YORK","ONE NEW YORK PLAZA, SUITE 4600, NEW YORK, NY, UNITED STATES","0029-8549","1432-1939",NA,"OECOLOGIA","Oecologia","OCT",2020,"194","1-2",NA,NA,NA,NA,"27","40",NA,"10.1007/s00442-020-04738-1",NA,"SEP 2020",14,"Ecology","Environmental Sciences & Ecology","OA9KW","WOS:000565500300002",32876763,"Green Published, hybrid",NA,NA,"2021-09-23",NA
"16","J","Mosher, SG; Crowley, BE; Yanes, Y; Diefendorf, AF; Barone, R",NA,NA,NA,"Mosher, Stella Grace; Crowley, Brooke Erin; Yanes, Yurena; Diefendorf, Aaron Fuller; Barone, Ruben",NA,NA,"Spatial variability in foliar carbon and nitrogen isotope values on Tenerife reflects both climate and soils: Establishing a framework for future work","ACTA OECOLOGICA-INTERNATIONAL JOURNAL OF ECOLOGY",NA,NA,"English","Article",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Delta(leaf); delta N-15; Temperature; Precipitation; Relative humidity; Soil weight %N","N-15 NATURAL-ABUNDANCE; WATER-USE EFFICIENCY; LAUREL FOREST; STABLE-ISOTOPES; CANARY-ISLANDS; NUTRIENT CONCENTRATIONS; GLOBAL PATTERNS; PLANTS; DISCRIMINATION; CHENOPODIACEAE","Tenerife Island is well-known for its biodiversity. It boasts the highest elevation in the Atlantic Ocean and its northern and southern slopes have varying moisture and temperature gradients. Consequently, there are multiple spatially discrete vegetation zones, or biomes, recognized on the island that roughly follow elevation. We investigated the extent to which climatic variables as well as soil nitrogen isotope values (delta N-15) and weight %N influence spatial isotopic variability in C-3 plants during the rainy season and assessed the degree to which foliar carbon isotope discrimination (Delta(leaf)) and delta N-15 values are able to distinguish biomes. Mean Annual Precipitation explained 71% and 55% of the spatial variability in Delta(leaf) and delta N-15 values, respectively. Overall, foliar delta N-15 values tracked those in soils, and soil %N was negatively correlated with both soil and foliar delta N-15 values. However, there was considerable variability among co-occurring species, as well as among sites within the same biome, which obscured trends among biomes. As a result, only a few biomes were isotopically distinct: Broad-leaved evergreen forest and sub-desert coastal scrub on the northern slope, and summit scrub and sub-desert coastal scrub on the southern slope. Further investigation into the influence of coastal orientation, topography, plant physiology, soil characteristics, as well as seasonal and inter-annual climate variability on foliar isotope values would be fruitful. Nevertheless, these results provide baseline information for researchers seeking to interpret diet and mobility of animals and people, as well as environmental changes over time on Tenerife and other Macaronesian volcanic islands.","[Mosher, Stella Grace; Crowley, Brooke Erin; Yanes, Yurena; Diefendorf, Aaron Fuller] Univ Cincinnati, Dept Geol, Geol & Phys Bldg, Cincinnati, OH 45221 USA; [Crowley, Brooke Erin] Univ Cincinnati, Dept Anthropol, Cincinnati, OH 45221 USA; [Barone, Ruben] C Eduardo Zamacois 13-3 A, Santa Cruz De Tenerife 38005, Canary Islands, Spain; [Mosher, Stella Grace] Univ Utah, Dept Geog, Salt Lake City, UT 84112 USA","Crowley, BE (corresponding author), Univ Cincinnati, Dept Geol, Geol & Phys Bldg, Cincinnati, OH 45221 USA.","brooke.crowley@uc.edu",NA,"Crowley, Brooke/0000-0002-8462-6806; Mosher, Stella/0000-0003-2761-9199","University of Cincinnati; Sigma Xi; United States of America National Science Foundation [EAR-1229114]","This research was funded by the University of Cincinnati, a Sigma Xi Grant in Aid of Research to SGM, and the United States of America National Science Foundation [grant No. EAR-1229114] to AFD and BEC.",NA,90,1,1,6,11,"ELSEVIER","AMSTERDAM","RADARWEG 29, 1043 NX AMSTERDAM, NETHERLANDS","1146-609X","1873-6238",NA,"ACTA OECOL","Acta Oecol.-Int. J. Ecol.","NOV",2020,"109",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"103647","10.1016/j.actao.2020.103647",NA,NA,14,"Ecology","Environmental Sciences & Ecology","OV9YU","WOS:000592556800003",NA,NA,NA,NA,"2021-09-23",NA
"17","J","Alderman, R; Tuck, GN; Castillo-Jordan, C; Haddon, M; Punt, AE",NA,NA,NA,"Alderman, R.; Tuck, G. N.; Castillo-Jordan, C.; Haddon, M.; Punt, A. E.",NA,NA,"Macquarie Island's northern giant petrels and the impacts of pest eradication on population abundance","ECOLOGICAL MODELLING",NA,NA,"English","Article",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Macronectes halli; Non-target poisoning; Recovery time; Population response; Bayesian model","CLIMATE-CHANGE; SOUTH GEORGIA; MACRONECTES; MANAGEMENT; FISHERIES; DYNAMICS; STOCK; SEA; PATTERNS; SURVIVAL","Pest eradication conducted over the years 2010 to 2014 at Macquarie Island successfully eradicated introduced rabbits, rats and mice from this sub-Antarctic island. The initial aerial baiting phase in the winters of 2010 and 2011 resulted in significant mortality of several native seabird species through primary and secondary ingestion of brodifacoum bait. A species of key concern is the northern giant petrel (Macronectes halli), which, although relatively abundant and increasing on Macquarie Island, is listed as threatened under Australian legislation and was one of the species most affected by poisoning. We use a Bayesian approach to estimate the total mortality and the response of the population to the poisoning event over the short- to medium-term. We then considered how population abundance might respond over the ensuing years. Projections of population trajectories suggest a greater than 50% probability of recovery to the pre-poisoning levels of 2009 breeding pairs by 2017. This modelling approach could be applied to future planned eradications to quantify the mortality and recovery of incidentally affected populations.","[Alderman, R.] Dept Primary Ind Pk Water & Environm, 3-134 Macquarie St, Hobart, Tas 7000, Australia; [Tuck, G. N.; Castillo-Jordan, C.; Haddon, M.; Punt, A. E.] Castray Esplanade, CSIRO Oceans & Atmosphere, Hobart, Tas 7000, Australia; [Punt, A. E.] Univ Washington, Sch Aquat & Fishery Sci, Seattle, WA 98195 USA","T