, populations and groups with the maximum similarity belonged to comparable latitudes. Populations grown in similar annual mean temperature; mean August and mean January temperatures, and annual precipitation showed the maximum similarity. Ultimately we may conclude that phenotypic populations may be valuable features of wild barley populations in employing the most suitable weed management approach.","[Hosseini, Mojtaba] Ferdowsi Univ Mashhad, Mashhad, Iran; [Ghorbani, Reza; Mohassel, Mohammad Hassan Rashed] Ferdowsi Univ Mashhad, Fac Agr, Dept Agrotechnol, Mashhad, Iran; [Yassaie, Mohsen] AREEO, Fars Agr & Nat Resources Res & Educ Ctr, Seed & Plant Improvement Res Dept, Shiraz, Iran","Ghorbani, R (corresponding author), Ferdowsi Univ Mashhad, Fac Agr, Dept Agrotechnol, Mashhad, Iran.","reza-ghorbani@um.ac.ir",NA,"Hosseini, mojtaba/0000-0001-7539-6730; Hosseini, Mojtaba/0000-0002-9942-529X","Faculty of Agriculture, Ferdowsi University of Mashhad, Iran","The authors gratefully acknowledge the Faculty of Agriculture, Ferdowsi University of Mashhad, Iran for financial support. Authors also wish to thank Mrs. Ladan Jokar, (Fars agricultural and natural resources research and education center) for her guidance regarding to statistical analysis.",NA,44,2,2,2,24,"ELSEVIER","AMSTERDAM","RADARWEG 29, 1043 NX AMSTERDAM, NETHERLANDS","1146-609X","1873-6238",NA,"ACTA OECOL","Acta Oecol.-Int. J. Ecol.","FEB",2019,"95",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"19","25",NA,"10.1016/j.actao.2018.12.004",NA,NA,7,"Ecology","Environmental Sciences & Ecology","HP1DZ","WOS:000461406900003",NA,NA,NA,NA,"2021-09-23",NA
"30","J","Piyapong, C; Tattoni, C; Ciolli, M; Dembski, S; Paradis, E",NA,NA,NA,"Piyapong, Chantima; Tattoni, Clara; Ciolli, Marco; Dembski, Samuel; Paradis, Emmanuel",NA,NA,"Modelling the geographical distributions of one native and two introduced species of crayfish in the French Alps","ECOLOGICAL INFORMATICS",NA,NA,"English","Article",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"Alps; Crayfish; Invasive species; MaxEnt modelling","FRANCE; PLAGUE; EXCRETION; CLIMATE; WORLD","The French Alps is an important area for several species of crayfish; some species are native in this region and several were introduced by humans. The present study aimed at modelling the distributions of these two cate-gories of species and find the significant environmental variables to explain these distributions. Field sampling was performed in this region in 2014 resulting in enough data for modelling the distribution of three species, one native (the white-clawed crayfish, Austropotamobius pallipes) and two introduced from North America (the spiny cheek crayfish, Faxonius limosus, and the signal crayfish, Pacifastacus leniusculus). Environmental data were collected from different sources and included altitude, slope, land cover, and several water quality measures such as nitrate and ammonium concentrations. The two introduced species showed different influential variables compared to the white-clawed crayfish. Currently, it is unlikely that the two introduced species affect negatively the native white-clawed crayfish. The most important threat for this species seems to be the increase of temperature caused by global warming. If the introduced species continue to spread, they may provide a synergy with the increase of temperature and threaten the native populations. It appears crucial to continue the monitoring of these species in this area. Future investigations should be carried out to understand the relationships between present crayfish spatial distribution and pathogens carried by alien species as these might be critical factors mediating the interactions among these species.","[Piyapong, Chantima] Burapha Univ, Dept Biol, Fac Sci, Chon Buri 20131, Thailand; [Tattoni, Clara; Ciolli, Marco] Univ Trento, Lab Ecol, Dipartimento Ingn Civile Ambientale & Meccan, Trento, Italy; [Tattoni, Clara] Univ Firenze, DAGRI Dipartimento Sci & Tecnol Agr Alimentari Am, Florence, Italy; [Ciolli, Marco] Univ Trento, Ctr Agr Food & Environm C3A, I-38010 San Michele All Adige, Italy; [Dembski, Samuel] Agence Francaise Biodivers, Paris, France; [Paradis, Emmanuel] Univ Montpellier, CNRS, EPHE, ISEM,IRD, Montpellier, France","Paradis, E (corresponding author), Univ Montpellier, CNRS, EPHE, ISEM,IRD, Montpellier, France.","Emmanuel.Paradis@ird.fr","Tattoni, Clara/AAG-6917-2020; Ciolli, Marco/D-8613-2014","Tattoni, Clara/0000-0003-1555-5669; Ciolli, Marco/0000-0001-8370-9039","French-Thai Cooperation Program in Higher Education and Research (2015-2016); ASEA-UNINET [ICM-2016-03779]","We wish to thank all the agents working at the French Agency for Biodiversity who performed the crayfish observations, Leopold Fureder for welcoming the first author in the University of Innsbruck, and Yorick Reyjol for help to obtain the data analysed in this study. We are grateful to the reviewer for the constructive comments on a previous version of this paper. Funding was provided by the French-Thai Cooperation Program in Higher Education and Research (2015-2016) for the project Analysis of Biodiversity in R (to CP and EP), and ASEA-UNINET on behalf of the Austrian Federal Ministry of Science, Research and Economy (Ernst Mach-Stipendien: ICM-2016-03779 to CP). This is publication ISEM-SUD 2020-200.",NA,49,1,1,0,6,"ELSEVIER","AMSTERDAM","RADARWEG 29, 1043 NX AMSTERDAM, NETHERLANDS","1574-9541","1878-0512",NA,"ECOL INFORM","Ecol. Inform.","NOV",2020,"60",NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,NA,"101172","10.1016/j.ecoinf.2020.101172",NA,NA,9,"Ecology","Environmental Sciences & Ecology","OY1BY","WOS:000593989600002",NA,NA,NA,NA,"2021-09